[`LookAt`](https://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/Transform.LookAt.html) takes an absolute world position Vector. You are passing in a **direction** Vector returned by [`Vector3.Cross`](https://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/Vector3.Cross.html) which is not quite what you want.

---

I would simply give the Sphere object a `SphereCollider` (if it doesn&#39;t have one anyway).

Then on the camera you could have a script using [`Collider.ClosestPoint`](https://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/Collider.ClosestPoint.html) and use the target position as a reference.

This position you can then pass into `LookAt`

something like

    public Collider sphereCollider;

    public void LookAtTarget(Transform target)
    {
        var position = sphereCollider.ClosestPoint(target.position);

        transform.LookAt(position);
    }

This should center the Camera on the point exactly &quot;under&quot; the target object on the Sphere surface thus that the Sphere surface fills half of the screen.

