Each solution presented assumes all data about an individual person exists on a single line.

Since each output from [Select-String][1] will be one [MatchInfo][2] object per line in the file, you can just join the `Value` property values for each object.

    Select-String -Path $input_path -Pattern $regex -AllMatches |
        Foreach-Object {$_.Matches.Value -join &quot;,&quot;} &gt; $output_file

All of this assumes that the order of your matches is predictable in your file. If they differ from that schema, then this becomes slightly more complex.


----------

If you would change up your regex to use named capture groups, your results could be more predictable with an unordered file. You still need to maintain a field format in the file though.

    $regex = &#39;\b(?&lt;ID&gt;\d{8})\b|\b(?&lt;Name&gt;[A-Z][a-zA-Z]*\s[A-Z][a-zA-Z]*)\b|\b(?&lt;Section&gt;[A-Z]+\d{3})\b&#39;
    
    Select-String -Path t.txt -Pattern $regex -AllMatches |
        Foreach-Object {
    	$groups = $_.Matches.Groups.where{$_.Success}
    	$ID = $groups.where{$_.Name -eq &#39;ID&#39;}.Value
    	$Name = $groups.where{$_.Name -eq &#39;Name&#39;}.Value
    	$Section = $groups.where{$_.Name -eq &#39;Section&#39;}.Value
    	$ID,$Name,$Section -join &quot;,&quot;
        }

The code above uses named capture groups with the syntax `(?&lt;captureName&gt;)`.


----------

Another alternative is to just use a [switch][3] statement with `-Regex` and `-File` parameters. Then capture groups do not even matter, but each regex must have a match per line.

    $output = switch -Regex -File $input_File {
        &#39;\b\d{8}\b&#39; {
    	    $ID = $matches[0]
        }
    
        &#39;\b[A-Z][a-zA-Z]*\s[A-Z][a-zA-Z]*\b&#39; {
    	    $Name = $matches[0]
        }
        &#39;\b[A-Z]+\d{3}\b&#39; {
    	    $Section = $matches[0]
        }
        &#39;$&#39; {
     	    $ID,$Name,$Section -join &quot;,&quot;
        }
    }
    $output &gt; $output_file


  [1]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.utility/select-string?view=powershell-6
  [2]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/microsoft.powershell.commands.matchinfo?view=pscore-6.2.0
  [3]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.core/about/about_switch?view=powershell-6

